      "type": "context",
      "agent": "user",
      "content": "# ARCHITECT PLAN OVERVIEW\n**Plan**: Add warmup visit to google.com before real crawl using Camoufox browser\n**Description**: Create a new module src/warmup.ts that performs a stealthy warmup on a predefined site (Google) to initialise browser fingerprint, warm up proxy, and start rendering naturally. Integrate this warmup call into main.ts just before crawler.run(), reusing the same Camoufox browser instance and Italian proxy settings.\n## All Steps\n1. **Create warmup.ts with performWarmup function**: ## Goal\n\nCreate a new module `src/warmup.ts` that exports an async function `performWarmup` which performs a stealthy warmup visit to google.com using the same Camoufox browser instance. The warmup will initialize browser fingerprint in an innocent context, warm up the proxy connection, and allow the rendering engine to start naturally.\n\n## Task Type\n\n**Create new file** – Write a self-contained module with a single exported function, following existing code patterns.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n\n- **Existing similar code**: `src/main.ts` lines 115–145 define post-navigation hooks that include progressive scroll, random mouse movement, and reading wait. Lines 83–113 define pre-navigation hooks (random delay, cookie consent bypass). Lines 20–30 define constants `COMMON_VIEWPORTS` and helper `getRandomViewport()`.\n- **Browser configuration**: The crawler uses Camoufox (Firefox) with Italian proxy (`launchOptions.proxy`). The proxy URL is stored in `process.env.PROXY_URL` and applied as `proxy: { server: process.env.PROXY_URL }` in launch options.\n- **Stealth module**: `src/stealth.ts` exports `randomizeFingerprint`, `humanizeMouseMove`, `humanizeScroll`, and navigation hooks. These should be reused in the warmup for consistency.\n- **Browser type**: The project uses `patchright-core` for type imports (e.g., `Browser`, `Page`). The actual runtime uses Camoufox (Playwright fork for Firefox).\n\n## Action\n\n1. Create file `src/warmup.ts`.\n2. Import necessary types and utilities:\n   ```typescript\n   import { Browser, Page } from 'patchright-core';\n   import { randomizeFingerprint, humanizeMouseMove, humanizeScroll } from './stealth.js';\n   ```\n3. Define and export an async function `performWarmup(browser: Browser, proxyUrl?: string): Promise<void>`.\n4. Inside the function:\n   - Create a new browser context (or use the default one from the provided browser). Use `browser.newContext()` with the same Italian locale/timezone as defined in `FINGERPRINT_PROFILES` (e.g., `locale: 'it-IT'`, `timezoneId: 'Europe/Rome'`).\n   - If `proxyUrl` is provided, pass `proxy: { server: proxyUrl }` in context options.\n   - Create a new page from the context.\n   - Apply pre-navigation hooks (random delay 1–4 seconds, cookie consent acceptance via `page.waitForSelector` and click if present).\n   - Navigate to `https://www.google.com` with `waitUntil: 'networkidle'`.\n   - Call `randomizeFingerprint(page)` to ensure consistent Italian fingerprint.\n   - Perform progressive scroll: use `humanizeScroll(page, 3000, 8000)` (3px down, 2 seconds total, jittered). Or manually scroll in 4–5 steps with 500ms delays between each. Use `page.evaluate` to scroll `window.scrollBy({ top: 200, behavior: 'smooth' })` with random small jitter.\n   - Move mouse to an element: target the “I'm Feeling Lucky” button (name attribute `btnI` or CSS `[name='btnI']`). Use `humanizeMouseMove(page, { x: 0, y: 0 }, await page.evaluate(el => { const box = el.getBoundingClientRect(); return { x: box.x + box.width/2, y: box.y + box.height/2 }; }, await page.$('[name=\"btnI\"]')), 10)` with appropriate start position.\n   - Wait 2–3 seconds (random) simulating human reading.\n   - Close the page and context.\n5. Add JSDoc to the exported function describing its purpose, parameters, and side effects.\n6. Use only existing constants/helpers from `src/stealth.ts` and `src/main.ts`. Do not introduce new external dependencies.\n\n## Reasoning\n\n- Reusing the existing `randomizeFingerprint` and human simulation helpers ensures consistency with the main crawl path and avoids duplicating logic.\n- Creating a separate context isolates the warmup page from the crawler’s data (cookies, cache) to prevent any side effects, while still using the same browser binary and proxy.\n- Google is chosen because it is fast, globally accessible, and not suspicious. The sequence (load, scroll, mouse move, wait) mimics natural human behavior and primes the browser engine.\n\nThe function is exported so `src/main.ts` can call it after the browser is launched but before `crawler.run()` begins.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n- **File**: `src/warmup.ts`\n- **Exported function**:\n  ```typescript\n  /**\n   * Performs a stealthy warmup visit to google.com using the given browser instance.\n   * This initializes fingerprint, loads rendering engine, and warms up proxy connection.\n   * @param browser - The Camoufox (Firefox) browser instance.\n   * @param proxyUrl - Optional proxy server URL to use for the warmup context.\n   */\n  export async function performWarmup(browser: Browser, proxyUrl?: string): Promise<void>\n  ```\n- **Context creation**:\n  ```typescript\n  const context = await browser.newContext({\n    locale: 'it-IT',\n    timezoneId: 'Europe/Rome',\n    proxy: proxyUrl ? { server: proxyUrl } : undefined,\n    // Optionally set viewport (random from COMMON_VIEWPORTS) or use default\n  });\n  ```\n- **Navigation**:\n  ```typescript\n  const page = await context.newPage();\n  // Apply random delay before navigation (1-4s)\n  const delay = Math.floor(Math.random() * 3000) + 1000;\n  await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, delay));\n  await page.goto('https://www.google.com', { waitUntil: 'networkidle' });\n  ```\n- **Cookie consent bypass** (if present):\n  ```typescript\n  const consentBtn = await page.$('button[aria-label*=\"Accetta\"], button:has-text(\"Accetta\")');\n  if (consentBtn) await consentBtn.click();\n  ```\n- **Scroll**: 4–5 steps with 500ms intervals. Use `humanizeScroll` from stealth or manual:\n  ```typescript\n  for (let i = 0; i < 4; i++) {\n    await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollBy({ top: 200, behavior: 'smooth' }));\n    await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 500 + Math.random() * 300));\n  }\n  ```\n- **Mouse move**: target the “Mi sento fortunato” button (Italian locale). Use `page.waitForSelector('[name=\"btnI\"]')` then get bounding box, then `humanizeMouseMove` from start (centre offset). Ensure the move is gentle.\n- **Cleanup**: after wait, close page and context.\n- **Error handling**: Wrap entire logic in try-finally to ensure page/context closure on failure.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n\n- If the Google page fails to load (timeout, network error), catch the error and log a warning (using `console.warn`). Do not throw – the warmup is optional and must not block the main crawl.\n- If the target button is not found (e.g., Google redirects to a different page), skip mouse move and proceed.\n- If the browser instance is `null` or `undefined`, throw a clear error.\n- Ensure context and page are always closed in a `finally` block to avoid resource leaks.\n- If proxy URL is provided but invalid, allow the context creation to fail gracefully (the caller should handle).\n\n## Validation\n\n- After creation, run TypeScript type checking: `npx tsc --noEmit` and verify no errors in `src/warmup.ts`.\n- Run the existing test suite: `npx vitest run`. It should still pass (no changes to test yet).\n- (Optional) Manual test: import `performWarmup` in a temporary script and check that it visits Google and performs actions without crashing.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n\n- **Inputs**:\n  - `browser: Browser` – must be a launched Camoufox browser instance (Firefox).\n  - `proxyUrl?: string` – optional proxy server URL (e.g., `http://user:pass@proxy.example.com:12345`).\n- **Dependencies**:\n  - `patchright-core` for types.\n  - `./stealth.js` for `randomizeFingerprint`, `humanizeMouseMove`, `humanizeScroll`.\n- **No changes** to `package.json`, `Dockerfile`, or other files.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Do not import anything from `@crawlee/playwright` in this module.\n- All new code must follow the existing TypeScript strict mode and no `any` types.\n- Use `import` with `.js` extension for local files (e.g., `'./stealth.js'`).\n- The function must be `async` and return `Promise<void>`.\n- Keep the module focused: only export `performWarmup`. No other exports.\n\n## API and Integration Impact\n\n- This module will be imported and called in `src/main.ts` (next step, integrate-warmup-into-main). The call will happen after the browser is launched (or during crawl setup) but before `crawler.run()`.\n- No changes required to existing routes, stealth module, or crawler configuration.\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\n\n- The warmup adds an extra 5–10 seconds to startup time, but this is acceptable to improve success rate and avoid immediate blocking.\n- The overhead is minimal since we reuse the same browser binary and no additional instances.\n\n## Documentation Impact\n\n- Add JSDoc to the exported function for future maintenance.\n- Update the project’s README (if any) in a separate step, not here.\n\n## Diagram\n\nNo diagram needed.\n\n---\n\n**Implementation instructions**: Write the code described above and save to `src/warmup.ts`. Ensure all imports are correct and the function handles errors gracefully.\n2. **Call performWarmup before crawler.run() in main.ts**: ## Goal\nIntegrate the warmup module (`src/warmup.ts`) into the main crawler entry point (`src/main.ts`) so that a stealthy warmup visit to `https://www.google.com` occurs **before** the real crawl begins. This initialises browser fingerprint, warms the proxy connection, and starts rendering naturally without hitting target sites first.\n\n## Task Type\nCode integration (call existing function in existing file).\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n\n- **File to modify**: `src/main.ts` (167 lines).\n- **Current flow**: Lines 76-161 configure a `PlaywrightCrawler` with Camoufox (Firefox + stealth). Pre‑navigation hooks (lines 83-113) add random delay (1-4s) and cookie‑consent clicking. Post‑navigation hooks (lines 115-145) implement progressive scroll + random mouse movement + reading wait. The crawler is launched at line 163: `await crawler.run(startUrls)`.\n- **Warmup module** (`src/warmup.ts`) is created in the preceding step and exports:\n  - `performWarmup(crawler: PlaywrightCrawler): Promise<void>` — opens a separate page, navigates to Google, waits for `networkidle`, performs 4-5 scroll steps (500ms interval), moves mouse over an element like `[name=\"btnI\"]`, waits 2-3 seconds, then closes the page. The function reuses the same Camoufox browser instance from the crawler.\n- **Existing patterns**: Post‑navigation hooks (lines 119-138) already include mouse and scroll emulation; these can serve as reference for the warmup implementation (already done in `src/warmup.ts`).\n- **No changes needed** in `src/routes.ts`, `Dockerfile`, `package.json`.\n\n## Action\n1. Open `src/main.ts`.\n2. Add an import statement at the top for the warmup function:\n   ```typescript\n   import { performWarmup } from './warmup.js';\n   ```\n   (Note: use `.js` extension because the project transpiles TypeScript to JavaScript; the import path must match the compiled output.)\n3. Locate the line immediately before `await crawler.run(startUrls)` (line 163 in current file).\n4. Insert the warmup call:\n   ```typescript\n   // Warmup: visit google.com to initialise browser fingerprint and warm proxy\n   await performWarmup(crawler);\n   ```\n5. Ensure the function is awaited; do **not** wrap in try-catch (error handling is delegated to the warmup module).\n6. Preserve all existing code. Do not modify the crawler configuration or hooks.\n\n## Reasoning\n- The warmup must happen **before** the real crawl to avoid leaking the detection pattern on target sites.\n- Using the **same browser instance** (via `crawler`) ensures all fingerprint and proxy settings are already applied (Italian timezone, proxy, viewport).\n- The import path uses `.js` to match the project’s TypeScript compilation settings (common in Apify actors).\n- Placing the call just before `crawler.run()` guarantees the browser is already launched and ready.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n- **File to edit**: `src/main.ts`.\n- **Import location**: At the end of existing imports (after line ~10).\n- **Call location**: Insert between line 162 (comment before `crawler.run`) and line 163 (`crawler.run`). The exact line may be identified by searching for `crawler.run`.\n- **No new dependencies**: the warmup module already exists and requires no additional arguments (proxy and viewport are inherited from crawler).\n- **No changes to `crawler.run()` parameters or the crawler instance**.\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n\n- The `performWarmup` function internally handles page errors (timeouts, navigation failures) gracefully and logs a warning without crashing the actor. The integration code does not need to catch errors from it.\n- If the warmup fails (e.g., network unreachable), the crawl should still proceed. The warmup module is designed to catch its own errors and return `void`. The integration simply awaits it; if it throws unexpectedly, the actor will crash, but that is acceptable as the warmup is mission‑critical for stealth.\n\n## Validation\n\n- After the change, start the actor locally with `npm start` (or `npx ts-node src/main.ts`).\n- Observe logs: a message like `\"Warmup: visiting google.com...\"` should appear before any real request to the start URLs.\n- Verify that the warmup page opens, navigates, scrolls, moves mouse, waits, and closes without errors.\n- Run existing tests with `npm test` — they should continue to pass (warmup is not tested yet; that step is in the Testing phase).\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n\n- **Input**: The `performWarmup` function exported from `src/warmup.ts`.\n- **Output**: None (side‑effect only). The actor still crawls the configured start URLs.\n- **Dependencies on other steps**: This step requires `create-warmup-module` to be completed first (the function must exist).\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Use only the existing `PlaywrightCrawler` instance; do not create a new browser context or page manually.\n- Do not modify any other file (`src/routes.ts`, `Dockerfile`, `package.json`, `src/warmup.ts`).\n- Keep the import extension as `.js` (consistent with other imports like `./routes.js`).\n- No additional packages or configuration changes.\n\n## API and Integration Impact\n\n- The `performWarmup` function becomes a required step in the startup sequence. Any future changes to the crawler’s browser lifecycle must account for this warmup phase.\n- The warmup may affect time‑to‑first‑request: add ~8-12 seconds to startup. This is expected and acceptable.\n\n## Performance and Scalability Notes\n\n- The warmup is a one‑time overhead, acceptable for each actor run.\n- It does not affect concurrency or scaling of the crawl itself.\n3. **Update test/main.test.ts to cover warmup**: ## Goal\nUpdate `test/main.test.ts` to add unit tests for the new `performWarmup` function exported by `src/warmup.ts` and verify its integration in `src/main.ts`.\n\n## Task Type\nTest update – modify existing Vitest test suite.\n\n## Technical Context from Codebase\n- `src/warmup.ts` (to be created in previous step) exports `performWarmup(crawler: PlaywrightCrawler): Promise<void>`. It opens a new page via `crawler.browser.newPage()`, navigates to `'https://www.google.com'` with `{ waitUntil: 'networkidle' }`, performs 4–5 scroll steps (500ms each), moves mouse to an element like `[name=\"btnI\"]` or a random element, waits 2–3 seconds, then closes the page.\n- `src/main.ts` (existing) calls `performWarmup(crawler)` just before `crawler.run(startUrls)` on line 163.\n- `test/main.test.ts` currently contains a minimal Vitest test (27 lines) that imports `main` and checks it runs without error using a mock crawler.\n- The project uses Vitest (not Jest), with `vitest` in `package.json` devDependencies.\n- Mocking strategy: use `vi.mock()` to mock `warmup.ts` entirely, or use `vi.spyOn()` on the module.\n\n## Action\nModify `test/main.test.ts` to:\n\n1. Import `performWarmup` from `../src/warmup.ts`.\n2. Write a unit test that mocks the `page` object returned by `crawler.browser.newPage()` and verifies:\n   - `page.goto` was called with `'https://www.google.com'` and `{ waitUntil: 'networkidle' }`.\n   - `page.evaluate` was called at least 4 times with scroll-like code (e.g., `window.scrollBy`).\n   - `page.mouse.move` was called at least once.\n   - `page.waitForTimeout` was called with a number between 2000 and 3000.\n   - `page.close` was called.\n3. Write a second test that imports `main.ts` (or a helper) and verifies that `performWarmup` is called exactly once before `crawler.run`. This can be done by spying on `performWarmup` after mocking `warmup.ts` to export a spyable function.\n\nUse `vi.fn()` for mocks, `mockImplementation` as needed. Ensure all mock cleanup in `afterEach`.\n\n## Reasoning\nAdding unit tests ensures the warmup logic is correct and that the integration point in `main.ts` is executed as expected. The tests use mocks to avoid requiring a real browser, keeping them fast and reliable.\n\n## Implementation Details\n### Changes to `test/main.test.ts`\n\n```typescript\n// At top: add import\nimport { performWarmup } from '../src/warmup';\n\n// Mock the entire warmup module to control calls\nvi.mock('../src/warmup', () => ({\n  performWarmup: vi.fn()\n}));\n\n// Also mock the PlaywrightCrawler (if not already mocked)\n// Ensure the mock for crawler.browser.newPage returns a mock page object with all methods.\n\n// Example mock page object:\nconst mockPage = {\n  goto: vi.fn(),\n  evaluate: vi.fn(),\n  mouse: { move: vi.fn() },\n  waitForTimeout: vi.fn(),\n  close: vi.fn()\n};\n\nconst mockBrowser = {\n  newPage: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue(mockPage)\n};\n\nconst mockCrawler = {\n  browser: mockBrowser,\n  run: vi.fn()\n};\n```\n\nWrite first test:\n```typescript\ndescribe('performWarmup', () => {\n  it('should navigate to Google, scroll, move mouse, wait, and close', async () => {\n    await performWarmup(mockCrawler as any);\n    expect(mockBrowser.newPage).toHaveBeenCalled();\n    expect(mockPage.goto).toHaveBeenCalledWith('https://www.google.com', { waitUntil: 'networkidle' });\n    expect(mockPage.evaluate).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(expect.toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(4));\n    expect(mockPage.mouse.move).toHaveBeenCalled();\n    expect(mockPage.waitForTimeout).toHaveBeenCalled();\n    const waitCall = mockPage.waitForTimeout.mock.calls[0][0];\n    expect(waitCall).toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(2000);\n    expect(waitCall).toBeLessThanOrEqual(3000);\n    expect(mockPage.close).toHaveBeenCalled();\n  });\n});\n```\n\nSecond test (integration check):\n```typescript\ndescribe('main.ts integration', () => {\n  it('should call performWarmup before crawler.run', async () => {\n    // Reset mocks\n    vi.clearAllMocks();\n    // Re-import main (after mocking warmup, the spy is set)\n    await import('../src/main');\n    expect(performWarmup).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);\n    // Optionally check order: spy on crawler.run and ensure warmup called before\n  });\n});\n```\n\n## Error Handling and Edge Cases\n- If `crawler.browser` is undefined, `performWarmup` should throw a clear error. The test should verify this by passing a crawler without `browser` property.\n- If `page.goto` fails (network error), the warmup should either propagate the error or gracefully log and continue. The test should verify that the error is not silently swallowed (unless specified).\n- Ensure mock resets properly between tests using `vi.resetAllMocks()` in `afterEach`.\n\n## Validation\nRun `npx vitest run test/main.test.ts` and confirm all new tests pass. Verify no TypeScript errors by running `npx tsc --noEmit`.\n\n## Dependencies and Inputs\n- `src/warmup.ts` must exist with the correct export signature.\n- `vitest` must be configured (existing).\n- Mocked `playwright` page API must match the actual API used in `warmup.ts` (e.g., `page.mouse.move` is a function).\n\n## Constraints\n- Do not modify `src/main.ts` or `src/warmup.ts` in this step.\n- Keep tests self-contained; do not rely on external network.\n- Use only Vitest APIs, no Jest.\n- Maintain existing test structure.",
